          "body": "No reading of Ezekiel 15 is complete without accounting for the recognition formula embedded in verse 7: 'Then you will know that I am the LORD.' This formula, which Block counts in over 72 occurrences throughout Ezekiel, is the stated telos of both Ezekiel's ministry and God's judgments. Judgment in Ezekiel is never nihilistic. It is always purposive — aimed at the restoration of true knowledge of God. The nation that forgot who the LORD was through decades of syncretism, idolatry, and false prophecy (catalogued in chapters 8, 13-14) will be taught again through catastrophe what they refused to learn through prophecy. The irony is profound: the vine-wood that was useless for any crafted purpose is useful for one thing — fuel for fire. And the fire that consumes Jerusalem will, in God's sovereign design, produce in survivors and witnesses a knowledge of His character that the temple, the sacrifices, and the festivals had failed to produce. This does not make the judgment less severe; it makes it coherent. The God who destroys Jerusalem in Ezekiel 15 is the same God who promises in Ezekiel 36-37 to regather, restore, and re-indwell His people — and the ground of that restoration will be the same formula: 'Then you will know that I am the LORD.'"
