        "number": 3,
        "title": "The 'therefore' pivot — Jerusalem given to the fire",
        "range": "15:6",
        "excerpt": "Therefore, thus says the Lord God, 'As the wood of the vine among the trees of the forest, which I have given to the fire for fuel, so have I given up the inhabitants of Jerusalem.'",
        "body": "Verse 6 is the chapter's pivot and its most devastating sentence. The *laken* (therefore) signals that the allegory is complete and the application has arrived. The structure of verse 6 is a point-for-point identification: the vine-wood given to fire for fuel = the inhabitants of Jerusalem. The equation is total and explicit. God does not say 'the inhabitants of Jerusalem are like vine-wood' — He says they ARE it. The metaphor has become predication.\n\nTwo elements of verse 6 demand careful attention. First, the divine agency: 'which I have given to the fire' and 'so have I given up the inhabitants.' The passive formulation of some English translations can obscure what the Hebrew makes explicit: God Himself is the one doing the giving. He is not standing by while Nebuchadnezzar acts; He is actively handing Jerusalem over. This is the same theological claim Paul makes in Romans 1:24, 26, 28 — God 'gave them over' — judicial abandonment as an act of divine justice. The covenant that was supposed to bring life has run its course; the covenant-breakers are handed to the consequences they chose.\n\nSecond, the totality: the inhabitants of Jerusalem are given 'as fuel' — not refined, not repurposed, not given a second chance to produce fruit. The purpose assigned is consumption. This is not vindictive; it is the logical end of a vine-wood allegory that has already established that burned vine-wood has no alternative use. The audience in Babylon who still hoped that Jerusalem's continuing survival represented divine favor now hears the verdict: the giving-up has already happened. The fire is still burning.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ken* (therefore, so) appears twice in verse 6, framing the equation: *as...so* (*ken...ken*). *Adonai YHWH* (Lord GOD) combines the sovereign title with the covenant name — the One who speaks is both covenant Lord and universal sovereign. *Yerushalaim* is the only proper name in the chapter, held until this pivot verse for maximum rhetorical impact."
