        "range": "15:7",
        "excerpt": "I set My face against them. Though they have come out of the fire, yet the fire will consume them. Then you will know that I am the LORD, when I set My face against them.",
        "body": "Verse 7 moves from the juridical (God giving up Jerusalem to fire) to the personal: 'I set My face against them.' The idiom is a divine-warfare declaration rooted in Levitical covenant curse (Leviticus 17:10; 20:3). To have God's face set against you is to have every covenant provision reversed. The Aaronic blessing of Numbers 6 — God's face shining, God's face turning toward — is the positive pole; God's face set against is the precise negation of that blessing. It is not mere divine displeasure; it is active, focused, personal opposition.\n\nThe sentence 'Though they have come out of the fire, yet the fire will consume them' is the oracle's most pastorally pointed claim. The exiles in Babylon — and especially the Jerusalemites still in the city — were interpreting survival as vindication. They had been through partial judgment and remained. Surely this proved God's protection. Ezekiel answers: no. Coming through the fire is not the same as being vindicated by God. The fire that failed to consume them completely is simply the preliminary fire; a greater fire is coming that will. The argument from survival to divine favor is specifically and explicitly dismantled.\n\nThe recognition formula — 'Then you will know that I am the LORD' — repositions the entire oracle. Judgment in Ezekiel is never the last word. It is always the penultimate word before revelation. The fire that destroys Jerusalem will produce in survivors, in exiles, and in future readers a knowledge of God's character — His holiness, His faithfulness to His covenant, His sovereignty over history — that the years of prosperity and false prophecy had extinguished. Calvin observed that this is how God's severity and mercy are finally the same act: the severity that destroys false confidence is the mercy that creates true knowledge.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Paneh* (face) twice in v.7 — the repetition is emphatic. *Sum paneh* (set My face) is a fixed idiom of hostile resolve (cf. Lev 17:10; 20:3, 5, 6; Jer 21:10; Ezek 14:8). *Yada* (know) — the recognition formula (*yadatem ki ani YHWH*) occurs 72+ times in Ezekiel; it is the stated goal of every judgment oracle in the book."
